### PaperPoint:
Recent developments in 2007 led to the ability to capture handwriting digitally and the us of paper as an interactive medium. Taking full advantage of this, Signer and Norrie made a tool that allowed presenters to control and annotate their slides during presentations by drawing on specially printed handouts of the slides. 

When discussion their tool, they start with defending the qualities of paper which make it superior to digital media, stating that its advantages make it superior to digital media, which seems to have been the case when this tool was made, they state that the advantages of paper are its easy of annotation, the preferences of users to write on paper as opposed to tablet PC's, which may be due to the clunkiness or novelty of said technology at the time, for other advantages they point towards paper being cheap, light, easily carried and being able to be viewed from different orientations, with them contrasting this to digital displays, stating them being heavy, expensive, awkward to carry and needing to be positioned in front of them to use them.      However, it seems that these are not as true in 2026 as they were in 2007, were it would be easier to argue the price of a fully digital solution, seeing as the cost of use for our implementation would be nothing, as everyone already owns a smartphone, hence the price being even lower. Comparing the ease of carrying we could again argue in favour of the digital solutions, seeing as you can have a cellphone and a USB stick in your pockets and be able to present without needing to bring anything of note at all, given that the presentation device is on-site, and in the case the presentation device is brought with the presenter, we can argue that the added weight and easy of carry is completely negligible, seeing as your phone weighs nothing compared to a laptop, and you can simply put a tablet next to your laptop and adding on average less than a kilogram to your carry weight, a final note here is that tablet devices no longer suffer from the orientation that a digital display, most likely a computer monitor, seemed to have had in their time.

Another note the writers of the paper make is that they often see presenters referring to a printed handout during a presentation, but this may be a dated statement as well, seeing as ive never seen paper in a presentation that wasnt in primary school.

They also note that some users apparently dont want to use the powerpoint presentation overview because it has 'too much information on the laptop screen which is a distraction' and they would prefer to see a mirror of what the audience is seeing, which is the weirdest take ive ever heard I reckon and I have heard a lot of bad takes.

Another thing they note is that handouts can be written on during the presentation to record questions and comments from the audience or note corrections to be made to the slide, but i again have never seen this before and i must admit it sounds kinda unprofessional to do that.

The paper states slides can be annotated in a very natural way by drawing and writing on the printed versions with the digital pen, which is fair, but now the same can be achieved with an iPad or tablet.

Other things of note: to make these interactive slides, they require extensive preparation, you require to make active areas on paper documents, which you must then place correctly ordered in the printer and then print your handouts on top of those activated papers, which sounds like something you cant exactly forget about or your presentation is fucked, with our tool if youve used it once you can use it eternally with the caveat that you havent forgotten to bring the device youre presenting with.

It seems the device they used, a magicomm g303 pen cost only around 10-15 euros so it isnt a notable cost, but its still something you must purchase and must remember to bring, same with your handouts, and from my own experience, the thing that is most important to bring is often the first thing you forget, if you need a doohickey to present, you *will* forget it at some point, your phone however is in your pocket and you would feel the absence of your laptop due to the weight.

A thing of note is them making it possible for users to have a specific sort of template to use for their presentations by way of printing extra bits of paper or stickers and pasting these onto a clipboard, which is similar to our idea of custom templates.

We also would not run into the issue of marks or annotations becoming disruptive, seeing as there will be no traces of use on the devices.

### TabletPoint
Tabletpoint states (in 2015/2016) that 30 million PPT's are made daily and PPT has 120 million users with an upward trend in the amount of presentations made daily, unsure if numbers still correct.

PPT follows linear sequence, same issue PaperPoint wished to solve, TabletPoint seems to be a spiritual successor of PaperPoint, utilising a newly release Tablet PC and Stylus pen, they address shortcomings of PaperPoint, such as lacking animations, requiring handout preparations, and "providing the user with useful functions to support better annotations" like allowing specific shapes to be drawn by the presenter and allowing the storage and reuse of drawings.

What we can see from PaperPoint and TabletPoint together is that presentations are very important, yet they seem far from otpimized, many solutions having been attempted to try to make presenting more fluid and easy for presenters, yet few of these gaining actual widespread adoption, possibly due to the entry barriers being deemed too high, i.e. people may not want to buy some kind of clicker, or a digital pen or a tablet with a stylus, possibly due to feeling that the frequency with which they present does not justify additional spending, even if this cost would greatly benefit their presenting. However, 68% of the global population has a smartphone, and these numbers rise to near universal ownership of smartphones in academia and  industry, which are the places where presentations are most common (https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9676861/, https://insights.samsung.com/2017/06/26/new-study-shows-growing-role-of-cellphones-at-work/). 

Seeing as presentations are still mainly done through PowerPoint on Microsoft Windows, with 95% of the presentation market being through PowerPoint (https://www.ebsco.com/research-starters/computer-science/microsoft-powerpoint), and Windows still accounting for 60.8% of the global PC market, as well as certain other operating systems having measures in place that already largely fix the issue we attempt to solve, e.g. Apple's screensharing or sidecar feature allowing users to control their presentations remotely or KDE Connect for Linux systems, we have decided to make our implementation's main focus be for presenting on Microsoft Windows architecture using PowerPoint, even though this may not be the current optimal way to present, but is just the most common.


